# By default, treat all files as binary: git never rewrites line endings
# on commit or checkout. This keeps assets and other binary files untouched
# and produces predictable results in different environments.
#
# Text *source* files are the exception: they are normalized to LF below,
# so edits on any OS (including Windows, where editors default to CRLF)
# commit as LF. This prevents the cross-OS CRLF/LF churn that previously
# left ~60 .go files and many .yaml/.xml/.json files committed as CRLF
# while their siblings were LF.
#
# Windows users contributing to this repo will need to use a modern version
# of git and editors capable of LF line endings. The attributes below make
# git enforce LF for source files regardless of editor settings.
#
# Windows .bat files are known to have multiple bugs when run with LF
# endings, and so they are checked in with CRLF endings, with a test
# to catch problems. (See https://github.com/golang/go/issues/37791.)
# They fall under the default "-text" below, so their committed bytes
# (including CRLF) are preserved.
#
# See https://github.com/golang/go/issues/9281.
# See https://adaptivepatchwork.com/2012/03/01/mind-the-end-of-your-line.
* -text

# Text source files: store LF in the repo and check out LF on every
# platform. Existing CRLF files were renormalized to LF in the commit
# that introduced these rules.
*.go            text eol=lf
*.proto         text eol=lf
*.yaml          text eol=lf
*.yml           text eol=lf
*.xml           text eol=lf
*.json          text eol=lf
*.csv           text eol=lf
*.sh            text eol=lf
*.md            text eol=lf
*.txtpb         text eol=lf
*.mod           text eol=lf
*.sum           text eol=lf
*.ts            text eol=lf
*.js            text eol=lf
.clang-format   text eol=lf
